            <thetext>If you use a config macro, like &#39;&quot;foo&quot; : &quot;${MYMACRO}&quot;&#39;, and MYMACRO is not 
defined, foo will contain &quot;${MYMACRO}&quot; as value.

This is usually not what you want. The ${...} indicate a macro replacement, and 
there is little chance that you want this to be the literal value. It would be 
better if unresolvable macros threw an exception.</thetext>
